4) Otherwise sends a Found message (possibly empty) indicating the DevAddr and RSSI of the heard neighbours. If no tag was heard, the seeking tag will be requested to perform another listening cycle with a lower RSSI threshold;
5) Receives a Timing message (and starts normal reporting). When not received, an empty Resync message is sent.
The server applies a uniform random distribution when assigning the slot numbers. To have a fast Seeking:
ÔÇ∑ Tags with slots n and n+1 must be in very different locations, so a seeking tag in any location quickly receives enough ‚Äúping‚Äù messages.
ÔÇ∑ The unallocated slots must be uniformly distributed to avoid having many similar indexes in one location when multiple tagged cars arrive.
Whether this assertion can be achieved at a large scale is yet to be validated at the customer site.
D. Reporting Tags When a tag location is known the tag continues to measure
and report the RSSI of its closest neighbours (see Fig. 5). Every Reporting tag:
1) Receives the Timing message, including:
o One Tx index corresponding to tag‚Äôs slot and a requested number of measurement cycles;
o Up to 8 Rx indexes corresponding to slots of its neighbours and a list of 3 measurement cycles when the Rx windows shall be opened.

2) Sends and receives ‚Äûpings‚Äú in the given measuring time-slots;
3) Sends a Report message that includes the DevAddr and RSSI of the heard neighbours;
4) Receives a next command from the server. When not received, stops ‚Äúpings‚Äù and sends a Resync message.
Each tag keeps transmitting pings until the next reporting slot, but the Rx window is opened in few measurement cycles only. To save energy the server selects first 3 measurement cycles when all of the selected neighbours are transmitting. It does not schedule any Rx slots when some of the neighbours are reporting and thus do not ‚Äúping‚Äù.
To ensure precise timing the server has to estimate the transmission time of the Timing message and subtract this value from the timing information sent to each tag.
The index numbers sent to the tag are relative to the start of the actual reporting period. The index 0 cannot be used as the tag needs some time to initialize the measurement.
To select the neighbours the server finds 8 closest tags in 8 different azimuth angles, preferring closer ones (as the precision is higher for lower distances) but aiming at having neighbours in all directions. As shown in Fig. 6 the server:
1) For each tag randomly selects an ‚Äúazimuth angle‚Äù and then selects a closest neighbour in each of the 8 sectors, each 45¬∞ wide (tags 3,6,7 in Fig. 6).
2) If there is no neighbour in a given azimuth angle, selects a second neighbour from an adjacent sector, minimizing the heuristics œÜd, where d is a distance of the neighbour and œÜ is the angle (in degrees) between the neighbour and the segment centre (tag 1).

