F. Power Consumption
The five main phases of a tag operation are shown in Fig. 8:
ÔÇ∑ In the Sleep phase the device turns off all unnecessary hardware. The accelerometer stays active as a movement detector;
ÔÇ∑ In the Active phase the Microcontroller prepares the tag for a new report or measurements;
ÔÇ∑ The LoRaWAN Tx/Rx phases depend on the DataRate and the length of the message. The measured current consumption range for the LoRaWAN Tx corresponds to the output power in a range between -1 and 16 dBm;
ÔÇ∑ Measurement (Ping) phase consists of two steps (Tx and Rx). Transmission is always at -1 dBm for about 10 ms, but the width of the reception window varies as explained before.

III. LOCALIZATION IN LORA MESH
A. RSSI to Distance Conversion The RSSI observed between tags gets converted into tag-
to-tag distances. The best results have been reached with the equation:
RSSI [dBm] = ‚Äì10p log10(d) + A,
where A is the received signal strength in dBm at 1 meter, d is the distance in metres and p is a propagation constant. The constant was selected empirically, based on calibration tests shown in Fig. 10.

