3) Compute the best rank-2 approximation U2 Œ£2 U2T (two largest eigenvalues) of (‚àí1/2)LDÃÇ L;
4) Return the x-y coordinates XÃÇ = U2 Œ£21/2.

The Multi-Dimensional Scaling (MDS) algorithm produces proportional coordinates XÃÇ that are arbitrarily rotated, scaled or inverted. To estimate parameters of the corrective transformation and calculate the absolute coordinates YÃÇ in meters we designed the following approach:

1) Each site is divided into multiple (>3) zones and for each zone the absolute x-y coordinates ZÃÇ (in meters) of the zone centre are determined;

2) Each Reporting tag is assigned to a cluster depending on in which zone it is physically located;
3) Centroid of each tag cluster CÃÇ = mean(XÃÇ i) is calculated in the proportional coordinates and an affine transformation f is estimated such that ZÃÇ = f (CÃÇ );

4) The tag coordinates are transformed as YÃÇ = f (XÃÇ ).

The affine transformation f (A) = cRA + T is estimated using the standard Umeyama algorithm [5] as follows:
1) Calculate a covariance matrix cov(CÃÇ ,ZÃÇ ) and a variance var(CÃÇ );

2) Calculate a singular-value decomposition UDVT of cov(CÃÇ ,ZÃÇ );

3) Calculate the estimated rotation matrix R = USVT,

scale factor c = tr(DS) / var(CÃÇ ),

and translation T = mean(ZÃÇ ) ‚Äì cR mean(CÃÇ ),

